iv><pre class="code-block__code !my-0 !rounded-lg !text-sm !leading-relaxed" style="background: transparent; color: rgb(171, 178, 191); text-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 0px 1px; font-family: var(--font-mono); direction: ltr; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; line-height: 1.5; tab-size: 2; hyphens: none; padding: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0px; overflow: auto; border-radius: 0.3em;"><code class="language-latex" style="background: transparent; color: rgb(171, 178, 191); text-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 0px 1px; font-family: var(--font-mono); direction: ltr; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; line-height: 1.5; tab-size: 2; hyphens: none;"><span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\section</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">Case Studies in Namespace Collapse</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\subsection</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">Email and the Spam Wars</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span>Email provides the canonical example of namespace collapse under adversarial 
</span><span>pressure. Early email systems treated sender addresses as declarative strings 
</span><span><span>with no cryptographic verification </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">RFC821</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>. As spam emerged, the 
</span></span><span>namespace became valueless: sender addresses conveyed no information about 
</span><span>actual origin.
</span><span>
</span><span>The response—SPF, DKIM, DMARC—represents gradual retrofitting of cryptographic 
</span><span>binding onto a fundamentally broken substrate. These protocols work only when 
</span><span>universally deployed and strictly enforced, conditions rarely met in practice. 
</span><span>The result is partial recovery: legitimate institutional email can be verified, 
</span><span>but individual user addresses remain forgeable.
</span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\subsection</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">Domain Name Squatting and Typosquatting</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span>The DNS namespace exhibits different failure modes. Domain names are globally 
</span><span>unique and persistently bound, satisfying the formal requirements of namespace 
</span><span><span>coherence. However, visual similarity enables </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\emph</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span>perceptual</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> laundering: 
</span></span><span>users cannot reliably distinguish "paypa1.com" from "paypal.com" or 
</span><span>"аррӏе.com" (using Cyrillic characters) from "apple.com".
</span><span>
</span><span>This demonstrates that namespace coherence is necessary but insufficient. 
</span><span>The mapping between symbols and referents must be not only unique but 
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\emph</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span>perceptually distinguishable</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> under realistic human attention limits.
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\subsection</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">Blue Check Crisis: Twitter/X 2022--2023</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span>The November 2022 decision to offer verified badges for purchase without 
</span><span>identity verification represents an accelerated experiment in namespace 
</span><span>laundering. Within 48 hours, impersonation accounts mimicking major brands, 
</span><span>public figures, and institutions proliferated. The symbolic value of the 
</span><span><span>verification badge collapsed immediately </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">NewYorkTimes2022</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>.
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">[</span><span>Add newspaper citations on the blue check chaos</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">]</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span>The incident demonstrates that namespace coherence cannot be sold as a 
</span><span>commodity. Once verification becomes available without binding constraints, 
</span><span>it ceases to verify anything.</span></code></pre></div></div>
