iv><pre class="code-block__code !my-0 !rounded-lg !text-sm !leading-relaxed" style="background: transparent; color: rgb(171, 178, 191); text-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 0px 1px; font-family: var(--font-mono); direction: ltr; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; line-height: 1.5; tab-size: 2; hyphens: none; padding: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0px; overflow: auto; border-radius: 0.3em;"><code class="language-latex" style="background: transparent; color: rgb(171, 178, 191); text-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 0px 1px; font-family: var(--font-mono); direction: ltr; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; line-height: 1.5; tab-size: 2; hyphens: none;"><span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\subsection</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">Theoretical Results</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\begin</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">theorem</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">[</span><span>Impossibility of Recidivism Detection Without Memory</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">]</span><span>
</span></span><span>In a system where identity mappings are memoryless (each observation is 
</span><span>conditionally independent of past observations given the current identifier), 
</span><span>no algorithm can detect recidivism with probability greater than random chance.
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\end</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">theorem</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\begin</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">proof</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">[</span><span>Proof sketch</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">]</span><span>
</span></span><span><span>Let </span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$X_t$</span><span> denote the true agent at time </span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$t$</span><span> and </span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$Y_t$</span><span> the observed identifier. 
</span></span><span><span>If the system is memoryless, then </span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$P(X_t | Y_1, </span><span class="token equation equation-command" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\ldots</span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">, Y_t) = P(X_t | Y_t)$</span><span>. 
</span></span><span><span>Given that identifiers can be freely created, </span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$P(X_t | Y_t)$</span><span> is uniform over 
</span></span><span>all possible agents. Therefore, no accumulation of evidence is possible, and 
</span><span><span>detection probability equals the base rate. </span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$</span><span class="token equation equation-command" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\square</span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$</span><span>
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\end</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">proof</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\begin</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">theorem</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">[</span><span>Cost Asymmetry Under Namespace Laundering</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">]</span><span>
</span></span><span><span>In a system where creating new identities costs </span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$c_{</span><span class="token equation equation-command" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\text</span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">{new}}$</span><span> and maintaining 
</span></span><span><span>reputation costs </span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$c_{</span><span class="token equation equation-command" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\text</span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">{rep}}$</span><span> per unit time, namespace laundering is 
</span></span><span><span>profitable when </span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$c_{</span><span class="token equation equation-command" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\text</span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">{new}} &lt; </span><span class="token equation equation-command" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\int</span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">_0^T c_{</span><span class="token equation equation-command" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\text</span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">{rep}} </span><span class="token equation equation-command" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\,</span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);"> dt$</span><span> for the 
</span></span><span><span>expected duration </span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$T$</span><span> before detection.
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\end</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">theorem</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">[</span><span>Proof omitted for space; follows from expected value calculation</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">]</span></span></code></pre></div></div>
