\title{Monetized Foreseeability:\\
Identity Churn, Scam Revenue, and the Structural Failure of Platform Governance}
\author{}
\date{}</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">\begin{document}
\maketitle</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">\section{Introduction: Foreseeability Without Ignorance}</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">Large online platforms frequently characterize fraud, impersonation, and scam activity as unavoidable externalities of scale. This framing relies on a presumption of partial ignorance: that harmful behavior emerges faster than it can be detected, classified, or prevented. Recent disclosures challenge this assumption in the case of Facebook and its parent company, Meta Platforms. Internal documents reviewed by Reuters in late 2025 demonstrate not merely awareness of large-scale abuse, but quantitative modeling of its extent, revenue contribution, and regulatory risk.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">According to Meta’s own internal estimates, its platforms expose users to tens of billions of scam attempts each day, including approximately fifteen billion paid scam advertisements. The company further projected that roughly ten percent of its annual advertising revenue derives from scams and other prohibited goods. These figures establish institutional foreseeability at scale. This essay argues that when harm is internally modeled, economically significant, and persistently tolerated through calibrated enforcement thresholds, continued monetization constitutes a design choice rather than an accidental failure.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">\section{Identity as a Disposable Resource}</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">Facebook’s advertising and page infrastructure permits rapid identity creation, minimal historical binding, and low-cost abandonment. Under such conditions, enforcement actions remove instances rather than actors. Accounts and pages function as consumables: once detected, they are discarded and replaced with near-identical successors. The cost of re-entry for abusive advertisers is negligible relative to the revenue they generate before removal.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">This identity churn undermines deterrence. When identity is inexpensive and history is not conserved, punishment loses meaning. Enforcement becomes episodic rather than corrective, and abuse becomes a rational strategy rather than a risky deviation.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">\section{Revenue-Calibrated Enforcement}</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">Internal Meta documents describe an enforcement regime in which advertisers are removed only when automated systems assign a fraud likelihood exceeding ninety-five percent. Advertisers assessed as likely but not sufficiently certain to be fraudulent are not removed; instead, they are subjected to higher advertising costs through so-called “penalty bids.”</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">This approach does not eliminate abuse. It monetizes uncertainty. By charging suspected fraudsters more to participate in advertising auctions, the platform preserves revenue while marginally reducing exposure. Meta’s own analyses acknowledge that higher prices on remaining scam advertisements offset much of the revenue lost through partial enforcement. Under these conditions, moderation operates not as harm prevention but as revenue optimization under reputational constraints.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">\section{Moderation as Reputational Risk Management}</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">Internal documents further indicate that enforcement priorities track reputational and regulatory risk rather than user harm. Impersonation of major brands, celebrities, or public figures receives disproportionate attention, while user-reported scams are frequently ignored or dismissed. In 2023, Meta safety staff estimated that approximately ninety-six percent of valid user reports of scam activity were rejected or unaddressed.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">This asymmetry reflects an institutional logic in which harm to users is treated as a degradation of experience, while harm to advertisers or regulators is treated as a business risk. Moderation under such conditions functions primarily to preserve platform legitimacy rather than to prevent exploitation.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">\section{Stabilization of Harm Through Economic Asymmetry}</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">Meta’s internal assessments anticipate regulatory fines of up to one billion dollars related to scam advertising. At the same time, the company estimates annual revenue from high-risk scam advertisements alone at several multiples of that figure. Regulatory penalties are thus priced into business projections as manageable costs rather than existential threats.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">When anticipated fines remain smaller than illicit revenue streams, harmful activity becomes economically stabilized. Enforcement efforts are calibrated to remain below thresholds that would materially disrupt revenue, producing a steady-state equilibrium in which abuse persists indefinitely.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">\section{Why User-Level Controls Cannot Succeed}</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">Blocking, reporting, and individual content filtering assume that abusive actors are rare and persistent. Internal estimates showing tens of billions of daily scam attempts invalidate this assumption. Under conditions of identity churn, enforcement removes artifacts rather than sources, and user-level actions cannot meaningfully reduce exposure.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">Responsibility under such conditions necessarily shifts from individual users to institutional design. Expecting users to protect themselves within a system that continuously regenerates abuse is both unrealistic and ethically inadequate.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">\section{Interpretive Framework: History, Irreversibility, and Entropy}</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">The failures described above can be understood as consequences of systems that treat identity as stateless and actions as reversible. When actions leave no binding historical trace, and when identities can be reset without cost, systems accumulate entropy rather than meaning. Harmful behavior does not dissipate; it diffuses.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">In contrast, history-bound systems treat identity as an accumulation of irreversible events. Actions alter future possibilities, and repetition carries increasing constraint. Under such regimes, abuse becomes costly because it cannot be erased without consequence. Trust becomes an informational property rather than a subjective feeling.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">From this perspective, Facebook’s governance failure is not primarily one of moderation capacity, but of foundational design. The platform lacks mechanisms that bind actors to their histories and lacks incentives that reward long-term coherence over short-term extraction.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">\section{Toward Constraint-First Platform Design}</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">Meaningful reform requires altering the structural conditions under which participation occurs. Three principles follow from the analysis above:</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">First, identity must be conserved. Accounts and advertisers should accrue irreversible history, such that enforcement actions compound rather than reset. Re-entry must carry increasing cost.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">Second, enforcement must operate upstream of monetization. Systems that profit from probabilistic harm cannot be neutral arbiters of that harm. Revenue and safety functions must be decoupled at the architectural level.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">Third, moderation must be evaluated in terms of entropy reduction rather than content removal metrics. The relevant question is not how many items are taken down, but whether the system converges toward lower rates of abuse over time.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">\section{Conclusion: Governance Beyond Denial}</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">When an institution internally models harm at scale, anticipates regulatory penalties, and constrains enforcement to protect revenue, continued abuse cannot be described as inadvertent. In such systems, moderation serves reputational maintenance rather than prevention.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">Absent structural changes that bind identity to history, raise the cost of re-entry, and realign incentives away from short-term monetization, fraudulent activity will remain a rational and profitable use of platform infrastructure. The problem is not a lack of data, nor a lack of tools, but a lack of constraint.</p><p class="whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">\newpage
