iv><pre class="code-block__code !my-0 !rounded-lg !text-sm !leading-relaxed" style="background: transparent; color: rgb(171, 178, 191); text-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 0px 1px; font-family: var(--font-mono); direction: ltr; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; line-height: 1.5; tab-size: 2; hyphens: none; padding: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0px; overflow: auto; border-radius: 0.3em;"><code class="language-latex" style="background: transparent; color: rgb(171, 178, 191); text-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 0px 1px; font-family: var(--font-mono); direction: ltr; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; line-height: 1.5; tab-size: 2; hyphens: none;"><span><span>Meta's internal assessments anticipate regulatory fines of up to one billion 
</span></span><span><span>dollars related to scam advertising </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">ReutersMeta2025</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>. At the same time, 
</span></span><span>the company estimates annual revenue from high-risk scam advertisements alone at 
</span><span>several multiples of that figure. This ratio mirrors patterns observed in prior 
</span><span><span>regulatory actions: the 2019 FTC settlement imposed a </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\$</span><span>5 billion penalty 
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">FTC2019Meta</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>, yet Meta's annual revenue that year exceeded </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\$</span><span>70 billion, 
</span></span><span><span>rendering the fine approximately 7\</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(92, 99, 112); font-style: italic;">% of annual revenue—substantial but not </span><span>
</span></span><span>existentially threatening.
</span><span>
</span><span>When anticipated fines remain smaller than illicit revenue streams, harmful 
</span><span><span>activity becomes economically stabilized </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Armour2016</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>. Regulatory penalties 
</span></span><span>are thus priced into business projections as manageable costs rather than 
</span><span><span>existential threats </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Langevoort2016</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>.</span></span></code></pre></div></div>
