iv><pre class="code-block__code !my-0 !rounded-lg !text-sm !leading-relaxed" style="background: transparent; color: rgb(171, 178, 191); text-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 0px 1px; font-family: var(--font-mono); direction: ltr; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; line-height: 1.5; tab-size: 2; hyphens: none; padding: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0px; overflow: auto; border-radius: 0.3em;"><code class="language-latex" style="background: transparent; color: rgb(171, 178, 191); text-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 0px 1px; font-family: var(--font-mono); direction: ltr; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; line-height: 1.5; tab-size: 2; hyphens: none;"><span><span>Blocking, reporting, and individual content filtering assume that abusive actors 
</span></span><span>are rare and persistent. Internal estimates showing tens of billions of daily 
</span><span><span>scam attempts invalidate this assumption </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">ReutersMeta2025</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>. Under conditions 
</span></span><span>of identity churn, enforcement removes artifacts rather than sources, and 
</span><span>user-level actions cannot meaningfully reduce exposure.
</span><span>
</span><span>Research on fraud victimology demonstrates that victim-blaming narratives 
</span><span>systematically underestimate the sophistication of modern scams and the 
</span><span><span>asymmetric information environments in which they operate </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Button2014,Cross2016</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>. 
</span></span><span>When platforms generate billions of fraudulent impressions daily, individual 
</span><span>vigilance becomes structurally inadequate. Responsibility under such conditions 
</span><span>necessarily shifts from individual users to institutional design 
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Citron2014,Roberts2019</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>.</span></span></code></pre></div></div>
