          ease-[cubic-bezier(0.165,0.85,0.45,1)] h-8 w-8 rounded-md active:scale-95 backdrop-blur-md Button_ghost__BUAoh" type="button" aria-label="Copiar al portapapeles" data-state="closed"><div class="relative"><div class="transition-all opacity-100 scale-100" style="width: 20px; height: 20px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;"><svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="transition-all opacity-100 scale-100" aria-hidden="true" style="flex-shrink: 0;"><path d="M12.5 3C13.3284 3 14 3.67157 14 4.5V6H15.5C16.3284 6 17 6.67157 17 7.5V15.5C17 16.3284 16.3284 17 15.5 17H7.5C6.67157 17 6 16.3284 6 15.5V14H4.5C3.67157 14 3 13.3284 3 12.5V4.5C3 3.67157 3.67157 3 4.5 3H12.5ZM14 12.5C14 13.3284 13.3284 14 12.5 14H7V15.5C7 15.7761 7.22386 16 7.5 16H15.5C15.7761 16 16 15.7761 16 15.5V7.5C16 7.22386 15.7761 7 15.5 7H14V12.5ZM4.5 4C4.22386 4 4 4.22386 4 4.5V12.5C4 12.7761 4.22386 13 4.5 13H12.5C12.7761 13 13 12.7761 13 12.5V4.5C13 4.22386 12.7761 4 12.5 4H4.5Z"></path></svg></div><div class="absolute top-0 left-0 transition-all opacity-0 scale-50" style="width: 20px; height: 20px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;"><svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="absolute top-0 left-0 transition-all opacity-0 scale-50" aria-hidden="true" style="flex-shrink: 0;"><path d="M15.1883 5.10908C15.3699 4.96398 15.6346 4.96153 15.8202 5.11592C16.0056 5.27067 16.0504 5.53125 15.9403 5.73605L15.8836 5.82003L8.38354 14.8202C8.29361 14.9279 8.16242 14.9925 8.02221 14.9989C7.88203 15.0051 7.74545 14.9526 7.64622 14.8534L4.14617 11.3533L4.08172 11.2752C3.95384 11.0811 3.97542 10.817 4.14617 10.6463C4.31693 10.4755 4.58105 10.4539 4.77509 10.5818L4.85321 10.6463L7.96556 13.7586L15.1161 5.1794L15.1883 5.10908Z"></path></svg></div></div></button></div></div><div class="text-text-500 font-small p-3.5 pb-0">latex</div><div><pre class="code-block__code !my-0 !rounded-lg !text-sm !leading-relaxed" style="background: transparent; color: rgb(171, 178, 191); text-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 0px 1px; font-family: var(--font-mono); direction: ltr; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; line-height: 1.5; tab-size: 2; hyphens: none; padding: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0px; overflow: auto; border-radius: 0.3em;"><code class="language-latex" style="background: transparent; color: rgb(171, 178, 191); text-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 0px 1px; font-family: var(--font-mono); direction: ltr; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; line-height: 1.5; tab-size: 2; hyphens: none;"><span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\section</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">Legal Framework: Foreseeability, Liability, and Section 230</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\subsection</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">The Section 230 Shield</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span>In the United States, Section 230 of the Communications Decency Act provides 
</span><span>platforms with broad immunity from liability for third-party content 
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">CDA230,Kosseff2019</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>. Courts have interpreted this provision to shield 
</span></span><span>platforms even when they have knowledge of harmful content, provided they did 
</span><span><span>not create or materially contribute to it </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Citron2014</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>.
</span></span><span>
</span><span>However, the doctrine of foreseeability complicates this shield when platforms 
</span><span>actively monetize known harm. If internal documents demonstrate that platforms 
</span><span>quantitatively model fraud revenue and calibrate enforcement to preserve it, 
</span><span>this may constitute material contribution beyond passive hosting. Legal scholars 
</span><span>have argued that Section 230 should not protect platforms that profit from 
</span><span><span>harms they can foresee and prevent </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Citron2014,Klonick2018</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>.
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\subsection</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">European Regulatory Responses</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span>The EU's Digital Services Act (DSA) </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">DSA2022</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> takes a different approach, 
</span></span><span>imposing affirmative duties on "Very Large Online Platforms" (VLOPs) to conduct 
</span><span>risk assessments and implement mitigation measures. Under Article 35, platforms 
</span><span>must assess "systemic risks" including fraud, and demonstrate that enforcement 
</span><span>measures are proportionate to identified harms.
</span><span>
</span><span><span>Meta's internal revenue projections from scam advertising </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">ReutersMeta2025</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> 
</span></span><span>would likely constitute evidence of foreseeable systemic risk under the DSA. 
</span><span>The question becomes whether enforcement calibrated to preserve that revenue 
</span><span>satisfies the proportionality requirement. Early indications from EU enforcement 
</span><span><span>suggest skepticism toward revenue-optimized moderation </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">GDPR2018Meta</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>.
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\subsection</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">Toward Strict Liability for Foreseen Harms</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span>This essay's analysis supports a shift toward strict liability for monetized 
</span><span>harms that platforms internally model. When a platform:
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\begin</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">enumerate</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\item</span><span> Quantifies harmful activity at scale
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\item</span><span> Estimates revenue derived from that activity
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\item</span><span> Calibrates enforcement to preserve revenue while managing reputational risk
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\end</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">enumerate</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>it can no longer credibly claim passive intermediation. Such conduct more closely 
</span><span><span>resembles knowing participation in prohibited transactions </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Langevoort2016</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>.
</span></span><span>
</span><span>A strict liability regime would not require proof of intent or specific knowledge 
</span><span>of individual violations. It would require only that platforms demonstrate 
</span><span>enforcement efforts proportionate to internally modeled harm. Platforms that 
</span><span>price regulatory fines into profit projections would face liability exceeding 
</span><span>illicit revenue, restoring economic incentives toward prevention rather than 
</span><span>monetization.</span></code></pre></div></div>
