iv><pre class="code-block__code !my-0 !rounded-lg !text-sm !leading-relaxed" style="background: transparent; color: rgb(171, 178, 191); text-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 0px 1px; font-family: var(--font-mono); direction: ltr; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; line-height: 1.5; tab-size: 2; hyphens: none; padding: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0px; overflow: auto; border-radius: 0.3em;"><code class="language-latex" style="background: transparent; color: rgb(171, 178, 191); text-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 0px 1px; font-family: var(--font-mono); direction: ltr; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; line-height: 1.5; tab-size: 2; hyphens: none;"><span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\section</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">Alternative Explanations and Responses</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\subsection</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">Argument: Technical Infeasibility</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\textbf</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span>Claim:</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> Meta's enforcement limitations reflect genuine technical 
</span></span><span>constraints in detecting sophisticated fraud at scale, not willful tolerance.
</span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\textbf</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span>Response:</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> This claim is contradicted by Meta's own internal modeling 
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">ReutersMeta2025</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>. If the platform can quantify scam volume at tens of 
</span></span><span>billions of daily impressions and estimate revenue contribution to within 
</span><span>percentage points, it possesses sufficient detection capability to enforce more 
</span><span><span>aggressively. The choice of a 95\</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(92, 99, 112); font-style: italic;">% confidence threshold is not dictated by </span><span>
</span></span><span><span>classifier accuracy but by revenue optimization </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Langevoort2016</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>.
</span></span><span>
</span><span>Moreover, the asymmetric treatment of brand impersonation versus user-affecting 
</span><span>scams demonstrates that enforcement priorities are driven by business risk 
</span><span><span>rather than technical limits </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Haugen2021</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>.
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\subsection</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">Argument: False Positive Risk</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\textbf</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span>Claim:</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> Lowering enforcement thresholds would generate unacceptable 
</span></span><span>false positives, wrongly excluding legitimate advertisers.
</span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\textbf</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span>Response:</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> This argument conflates immediate exclusion with graduated 
</span></span><span>response. Platforms could impose manual review requirements, escalating 
</span><span>verification burdens, or temporary suspensions for advertisers flagged with 
</span><span><span></span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$&gt;$</span><span>50\</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(92, 99, 112); font-style: italic;">% fraud likelihood—all measures that reduce harm without permanent exclusion.</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span>The fact that Meta instead implements penalty pricing </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">ReutersMeta2025</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> 
</span></span><span>reveals the true priority: preserving revenue from uncertain cases rather than 
</span><span>protecting users from probable harm.
</span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\subsection</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">Argument: User Responsibility</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\textbf</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span>Claim:</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> Sophisticated users should recognize scams, and platforms cannot 
</span></span><span>be expected to eliminate all fraud.
</span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\textbf</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span>Response:</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> When platforms internally estimate exposure at tens of 
</span></span><span><span>billions of scam attempts daily </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">ReutersMeta2025</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>, individual vigilance 
</span></span><span><span>becomes structurally inadequate </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Cross2016,Button2014</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>. Moreover, this 
</span></span><span>argument ignores power asymmetries: platforms possess comprehensive behavioral 
</span><span>data, fraud detection models, and infrastructure control, while individual users 
</span><span>operate with fragmented information.
</span><span>
</span><span>Legal frameworks increasingly reject victim-blaming in contexts of institutional 
</span><span><span>foreseeability </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Citron2014</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>. When platforms model and monetize harm at 
</span></span><span>scale, responsibility shifts from users to institutions.</span></code></pre></div></div>
