          ease-[cubic-bezier(0.165,0.85,0.45,1)] h-8 w-8 rounded-md active:scale-95 backdrop-blur-md Button_ghost__BUAoh" type="button" aria-label="Copiar al portapapeles" data-state="closed"><div class="relative"><div class="transition-all opacity-100 scale-100" style="width: 20px; height: 20px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;"><svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="transition-all opacity-100 scale-100" aria-hidden="true" style="flex-shrink: 0;"><path d="M12.5 3C13.3284 3 14 3.67157 14 4.5V6H15.5C16.3284 6 17 6.67157 17 7.5V15.5C17 16.3284 16.3284 17 15.5 17H7.5C6.67157 17 6 16.3284 6 15.5V14H4.5C3.67157 14 3 13.3284 3 12.5V4.5C3 3.67157 3.67157 3 4.5 3H12.5ZM14 12.5C14 13.3284 13.3284 14 12.5 14H7V15.5C7 15.7761 7.22386 16 7.5 16H15.5C15.7761 16 16 15.7761 16 15.5V7.5C16 7.22386 15.7761 7 15.5 7H14V12.5ZM4.5 4C4.22386 4 4 4.22386 4 4.5V12.5C4 12.7761 4.22386 13 4.5 13H12.5C12.7761 13 13 12.7761 13 12.5V4.5C13 4.22386 12.7761 4 12.5 4H4.5Z"></path></svg></div><div class="absolute top-0 left-0 transition-all opacity-0 scale-50" style="width: 20px; height: 20px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;"><svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="absolute top-0 left-0 transition-all opacity-0 scale-50" aria-hidden="true" style="flex-shrink: 0;"><path d="M15.1883 5.10908C15.3699 4.96398 15.6346 4.96153 15.8202 5.11592C16.0056 5.27067 16.0504 5.53125 15.9403 5.73605L15.8836 5.82003L8.38354 14.8202C8.29361 14.9279 8.16242 14.9925 8.02221 14.9989C7.88203 15.0051 7.74545 14.9526 7.64622 14.8534L4.14617 11.3533L4.08172 11.2752C3.95384 11.0811 3.97542 10.817 4.14617 10.6463C4.31693 10.4755 4.58105 10.4539 4.77509 10.5818L4.85321 10.6463L7.96556 13.7586L15.1161 5.1794L15.1883 5.10908Z"></path></svg></div></div></button></div></div><div class="text-text-500 font-small p-3.5 pb-0">latex</div><div><pre class="code-block__code !my-0 !rounded-lg !text-sm !leading-relaxed" style="background: transparent; color: rgb(171, 178, 191); text-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 0px 1px; font-family: var(--font-mono); direction: ltr; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; line-height: 1.5; tab-size: 2; hyphens: none; padding: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0px; overflow: auto; border-radius: 0.3em;"><code class="language-latex" style="background: transparent; color: rgb(171, 178, 191); text-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3) 0px 1px; font-family: var(--font-mono); direction: ltr; text-align: left; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; word-break: normal; line-height: 1.5; tab-size: 2; hyphens: none;"><span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\section</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">Conclusion: Governance Beyond Denial</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span>When an institution internally models harm at scale, anticipates regulatory 
</span><span>penalties, and constrains enforcement to protect revenue, continued abuse cannot 
</span><span><span>be described as inadvertent </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Langevoort2016</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>. In such systems, moderation 
</span></span><span><span>serves reputational maintenance rather than prevention </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Roberts2019</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>.
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\subsection</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">Immediate Reforms</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span>Three reforms could meaningfully alter incentive structures without requiring 
</span><span>platform redesign:
</span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\textbf</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span>1. Penalty Exceeding Revenue:</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> Regulatory fines for monetized harm should 
</span></span><span><span>exceed revenue derived from that harm by a factor of 2--3</span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$</span><span class="token equation equation-command" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\times</span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$</span><span>. Current 
</span></span><span><span>penalties function as cost-of-doing-business </span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Armour2016</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>. Penalties 
</span></span><span>exceeding illicit revenue would invert the economic calculus.
</span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\textbf</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span>2. Escalating Identity Costs:</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> Platforms should be required to implement 
</span></span><span>identity systems where re-entry costs increase exponentially with prior removals. 
</span><span><span>If an advertiser's tenth account costs 100</span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$</span><span class="token equation equation-command" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\times</span><span class="token equation" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">$</span><span> more than their first, 
</span></span><span>identity churn becomes economically prohibitive.
</span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\textbf</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span>3. Algorithmic Transparency Requirements:</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> Platforms should be required 
</span></span><span>to disclose enforcement thresholds, penalty pricing mechanisms, and the economic 
</span><span>models underlying moderation decisions. The DSA's transparency provisions 
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">DSA2022</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span> provide a foundation, but should be strengthened to require 
</span></span><span>disclosure of revenue optimization parameters.
</span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\subsection</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">Structural Alternatives</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span>Absent structural changes that bind identity to history, raise the cost of 
</span><span>re-entry, and realign incentives away from short-term monetization, fraudulent 
</span><span>activity will remain a rational and profitable use of platform infrastructure. 
</span><span>The problem is not a lack of data, nor a lack of tools, but a lack of constraint 
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Lessig1999,Scott1998</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>.
</span></span><span>
</span><span>Future systems must treat identity as infrastructure rather than content 
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">Zuboff2019</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>. This requires:
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\begin</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">itemize</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\item</span><span> Cryptographic identity binding with costly Sybil resistance
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\item</span><span> Historical accumulation that cannot be reset without consequence
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\item</span><span> Enforcement architectures where safety and revenue functions are structurally 
</span></span><span>decoupled
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\end</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">itemize</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span>Platforms built on such foundations would make monetized foreseeability 
</span><span>economically irrational rather than strategically optimal.
</span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\subsection</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token headline" style="color: rgb(209, 154, 102);">The Path Forward</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span>Meta's case demonstrates that hoping for voluntary reform from platforms whose 
</span><span>revenue depends on calibrated tolerance of harm is empirically unjustified 
</span><span><span></span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(152, 195, 121);">\cite</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">{</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(198, 120, 221);">ReutersMeta2025,Haugen2021</span><span class="token" style="color: rgb(171, 178, 191);">}</span><span>. Regulatory intervention must therefore shift 
</span></span><span>from reactive content removal mandates to structural requirements that alter 
</span><span>underlying incentives.
</span><span>
</span><span>When institutions possess the capacity to model harm, estimate its revenue 
</span><span>contribution, and optimize enforcement accordingly, continued monetization 
</span><span>represents a governance failure that no amount of content moderation can address. 
</span><span>Only architectural reform—binding identity to history, pricing harm above profit, 
</span><span>and requiring transparency in enforcement optimization—can restore alignment 
</span><span>between platform incentives and user protection.</span></code></pre></div></div>
